The error is in the loop that generates the output:

    for (int i=0; i&lt;=s.size(); i++) {
        cout &lt;&lt; s.top() &lt;&lt; &quot; &quot;;  
        s.pop();
    }  

Every time you execute `s.pop()`, the value returned by `s.size()` will be one less. So this means your loop condition will not check against the *original* size of the stack. And so you&#39;ll exit the loop sooner than expected.

It would work correctly if you would read `s.size()` just once, for instance by *starting* with that value:

    for (int i=s.size(); i &gt; 0; i--) {
        cout &lt;&lt; s.top() &lt;&lt; &quot; &quot;;  
        s.pop();
    }  

But you could just use a `while` loop:

    while (s.size() &gt; 0) {
        cout &lt;&lt; s.top() &lt;&lt; &quot; &quot;;  
        s.pop();
    }

**Idea**

  - Recursion can be considered as looping with a stack (the call stack).

  - Every call, if we take 2 elements at the top of the stack and push back the smaller one. If we continuously call until the stack is empty, the smallest element is the thing left at the last call. So, we can use bubble sort in this scenario.

**Pseudo code**
```
function actual_sort(stack) {
    for (let i=0; i&lt;stack.length; i++)
        sort(stack);
}
function sort(stack) {
    if (stack.length &lt; 2)
        return;
    let [a, b] = stack.pop(2);
    stack.push(min(a, b));
    sort(stack);
    stack.push(max(a, b));
